# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: reproducible-builds
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] Build automation encompasses both sequencing build operations via non-interactive interface tools and running builds on a shared server.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] Build automation tools allow sequencing the tasks of building software via a non-interactive interface.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] A *build system* or *build automation tool* is a programming tool or set of tools that automate the compiling and linking of source code into an executable program or library.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] They streamline the software development process by managing dependencies, resolving conflicts, and ensuring consistent builds across different environments.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] When software projects grow complex, their build steps may involve multiple programming languages or compiling units, making manual build processes increasingly cumbersome.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] Dependencies between code components necessitate careful ordering and potentially different tools for each piece.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] Managing these dependencies manually can quickly lead to version conflicts, stale binaries, and difficulty tracking updates, making solutions such as shell scripts too difficult to maintain.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] While individual developers might compile code directly, a robust build system is foundational to efficient software development in large organizations and teams, where automated builds become commonplace and most builds are triggered automatically rather than manually.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] Given the essential role of build systems, it is said that they act as "repositories of essential build knowledge".
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] They effectively eliminate roadblocks and accelerate development velocity by enabling engineers to share resources and results.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] An incremental build is a process within a build system where build tools use an incremental compiler to recompile only the parts of a software project that have changed since the last build, rather than rebuilding everything from scratch.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] This optimization reduces build time by leveraging dependency tracking, caching, and selective compilation.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] Incremental builds are especially valuable in large-scale software projects, where recompiling the entire codebase can be time-consuming and resource-intensive.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] By identifying and compiling only the modified components—such as source files, libraries, or modules—the build system ensures faster iteration cycles, enabling developers to test and debug changes more efficiently.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] The process relies on a dependency graph, which maps relationships between files, modules, or components in the project.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] When a change is detected, the build system traverses this graph to determine which parts of the project are affected and need to be recompiled.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] Modern build tools, such as Make, Gradle and Bazel, often incorporate incremental build capabilities to streamline development workflows.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] While incremental builds offer significant performance advantages, they also introduce challenges, such as ensuring the accuracy of dependency tracking and avoiding stale or inconsistent build artifacts.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] To address these issues, some build systems provide mechanisms for "clean builds," which rebuild the entire project from scratch to guarantee correctness when necessary.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] Because of this issue, incremental builds are rarely used in continuous integration systems, where correctness is preferred to compilation speed.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] Tools such as Make can be used via custom configuration file or using the command-line.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] Custom tools such as shell scripts can also be used, although they become increasingly cumbersome as the codebase grows more complex.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] Some tools, such as shell scripts, are task-oriented declarative programming.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] They encode sequences of commands to perform with usually minimal conditional logic.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] Some tools, such as Make are product-oriented.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] They build a product, a.k.a. target, based on configured dependencies.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] A build server is a server setup to run builds.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] In contrast to a personal computer, a server allows for a more consistent and available build environment.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] Traditionally, a build server was a local computer dedicated as a shared resource instead of used as a personal computer.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] Today, there are many cloud computing, software as a service (SaaS) websites for building.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] A continuous integration server is a build server that is setup to build in a relatively frequent way, often on each code commit.
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] A build server may also be incorporated into a tool for application release automation (ARA) or application lifecycle management (ALM).
[src:reproducible-builds/build-automation] Automating the build process is a required step for implementing continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD), all of which are considered best practices for software development.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] In computing, a **compiler** is software that translates computer code written in one programming language (the *source* language) into another language (the *target* language).
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The name "compiler" is primarily used for programs that translate source code from a high-level programming language to a low-level programming language (e.g., assembly language, object code, or machine code) to create an executable program.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] There are many different types of compilers which produce output in different useful forms.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] A *cross-compiler* produces code for a different central processing unit (CPU) or operating system than the one on which the cross-compiler itself runs.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] A *bootstrap compiler* is often a temporary compiler, used for compiling a more permanent or better optimized compiler for a language.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Compilers generally implement these phases as modular components, promoting efficient design and correctness of transformations of source input to target output.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Program faults caused by incorrect compiler behavior can be very difficult to track down and work around; therefore, compiler implementers invest significant effort to ensure compiler correctness.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] With respect to making source code runnable, an interpreter provides a similar function as a compiler, but via a different mechanism.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] An interpreter executes code without converting it to machine code.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Therefore, some interpreters execute source code while others execute an intermediate form such as bytecode.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] A program compiled to native code tends to run faster than when interpreted, while environments with a bytecode-intermediate-form tends toward intermediate-speed.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Alternatively, just-in-time compilation allows for native execution speed with a one-time startup processing time cost.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Low-level programming languages, such as assembly and C, are typically compiled, especially when speed is a significant concern, rather than having cross-platform support.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] For such languages, there are more one-to-one correspondences between the source code and the resulting machine code, making it easier for programmers to control the use of hardware.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] In theory, any programming language can be used via either a compiler or an interpreter, but in practice, languages tend to be used with only one or the other.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Nonetheless, it is possible to write a compiler for a language that is commonly interpreted.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] For example, Common Lisp can be compiled to Java bytecode (and then interpreted by the Java virtual machine), to C code (which can then be compiled again to native machine code), or directly to native code.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Theoretical computing concepts developed by scientists, mathematicians, and engineers formed the basis of digital modern computing development during World War II.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Primitive binary languages evolved because digital devices only understand ones and zeros and the circuit patterns in the underlying machine architecture.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] In the late 1940s, assembly languages were created to offer a more workable abstraction of the computer architectures.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Limited memory capacity of early computers led to substantial technical challenges when the first compilers were designed.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Therefore, the compiling process needed to be divided into several small programs.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The front end programs produce the analysis products used by the back end programs to generate target code.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] As computer technology provided more resources, compiler designs could align better with the compiling process.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] It is usually more productive for a programmer to use a high-level language, so the development of high-level languages followed naturally from the abilities offered by digital computers.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] High-level languages are formal languages that are strictly defined by their syntax and semantics which form the high-level language architecture.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The sentences in a language may be defined by a set of rules called a grammar.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Backus–Naur form (BNF) describes the syntax of "sentences" of a language.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] It was developed by John Backus and used for the syntax of Algol 60.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The ideas derive from the context-free grammar concepts by linguist Noam Chomsky.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] "BNF and its extensions have become standard tools for describing the syntax of programming notations.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Between 1942 and 1945, Konrad Zuse designed the first (algorithmic) programming language for computers named *Plankalkül* ("Plan Calculus").
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Zuse also envisioned a *Planfertigungsgerät* ("Plan assembly device") to automatically translate the mathematical formulation of a program into machine-readable punched film stock.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] While no implementation occurred until the 1970s, it presented concepts later seen in APL designed by Ken Iverson in the late 1950s.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] APL is a language for mathematical computations.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Between 1949 and 1951, Heinz Rutishauser proposed Superplan, a high-level language and automatic translator.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] His ideas were later refined by Friedrich L.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Compiler technology evolved from the need for a strictly defined transformation of the high-level source program into a low-level target program for the digital computer.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The compiler could be viewed as a front end to deal with the analysis of the source code and a back end to synthesize the analysis into the target code.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Optimization between the front end and back end could produce more efficient target code.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Early operating systems and software were written in assembly language.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] In the 1960s and early 1970s, the use of high-level languages for system programming was still controversial due to resource limitations.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] However, several research and industry efforts began the shift toward high-level systems programming languages, for example, BCPL, BLISS, B, and C.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] BCPL (Basic Combined Programming Language) designed in 1966 by Martin Richards at the University of Cambridge was originally developed as a compiler writing tool.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Several compilers have been implemented, Richards' book provides insights to the language and its compiler.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] BCPL was not only an influential systems programming language that is still used in research but also provided a basis for the design of B and C languages.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] BLISS (Basic Language for Implementation of System Software) was developed for a Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) PDP-10 computer by W.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Wulf's Carnegie Mellon University (CMU) research team.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The CMU team went on to develop BLISS-11 compiler one year later in 1970.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Multics (Multiplexed Information and Computing Service), a time-sharing operating system project, involved MIT, Bell Labs, General Electric (later Honeywell) and was led by Fernando Corbató from MIT.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Multics was written in the PL/I language developed by IBM and IBM User Group.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] IBM's goal was to satisfy business, scientific, and systems programming requirements.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] There were other languages that could have been considered but PL/I offered the most complete solution even though it had not been implemented.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] For the first few years of the Multics project, a subset of the language could be compiled to assembly language with the Early PL/I (EPL) compiler by Doug McIlory and Bob Morris from Bell Labs.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] EPL supported the project until a boot-strapping compiler for the full PL/I could be developed.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Bell Labs left the Multics project in 1969, and developed a system programming language B based on BCPL concepts, written by Dennis Ritchie and Ken Thompson.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Ritchie created a boot-strapping compiler for B and wrote Unics (Uniplexed Information and Computing Service) operating system for a PDP-7 in B.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Bell Labs started the development and expansion of C based on B and BCPL.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The BCPL compiler had been transported to Multics by Bell Labs and BCPL was a preferred language at Bell Labs.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Initially, a front-end program to Bell Labs' B compiler was used while a C compiler was developed.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] In 1971, a new PDP-11 provided the resource to define extensions to B and rewrite the compiler.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] By 1973 the design of C language was essentially complete and the Unix kernel for a PDP-11 was rewritten in C.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Steve Johnson started development of Portable C Compiler (PCC) to support retargeting of C compilers to new machines.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Object-oriented programming (OOP) offered some interesting possibilities for application development and maintenance.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] OOP concepts go further back but were part of LISP and Simula language science.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Bell Labs became interested in OOP with the development of C++.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] C++ was first used in 1980 for systems programming.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The initial design leveraged C language systems programming abilities with Simula concepts.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Object-oriented facilities were added in 1983.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The Cfront program implemented a C++ front-end for C84 language compiler.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] In subsequent years several C++ compilers were developed as C++ popularity grew.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] In many application domains, the idea of using a higher-level language quickly caught on.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Because of the expanding functionality supported by newer programming languages and the increasing complexity of computer architectures, compilers became more complex.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] DARPA (Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency) sponsored a compiler project with Wulf's CMU research team in 1970.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The Production Quality Compiler-Compiler PQCC design would produce a Production Quality Compiler (PQC) from formal definitions of source language and the target.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] PQCC tried to extend the term compiler-compiler beyond the traditional meaning as a parser generator (e.g., Yacc) without much success.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] PQCC might more properly be referred to as a compiler generator.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] PQCC research into code generation process sought to build a truly automatic compiler-writing system.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The effort discovered and designed the phase structure of the PQC.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The BLISS-11 compiler provided the initial structure.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The phases included analyses (front end), intermediate translation to virtual machine (middle end), and translation to the target (back end).
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] TCOL was developed for the PQCC research to handle language specific constructs in the intermediate representation.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Variations of TCOL supported various languages.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The PQCC project investigated techniques of automated compiler construction.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The design concepts proved useful in optimizing compilers and compilers for the (since 1995, object-oriented) programming language Ada.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The Ada *STONEMAN* document formalized the program support environment (APSE) along with the kernel (KAPSE) and minimal (MAPSE).
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] An Ada interpreter NYU/ED supported development and standardization efforts with the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) and the International Standards Organization (ISO).
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Initial Ada compiler development by the U.S.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Military Services included the compilers in a complete integrated design environment along the lines of the *STONEMAN* document.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Army and Navy worked on the Ada Language System (ALS) project targeted to DEC/VAX architecture while the Air Force started on the Ada Integrated Environment (AIE) targeted to IBM 370 series.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] While the projects did not provide the desired results, they did contribute to the overall effort on Ada development.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Other Ada compiler efforts got underway in Britain at the University of York and in Germany at the University of Karlsruhe.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] S., Verdix (later acquired by Rational) delivered the Verdix Ada Development System (VADS) to the Army.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] VADS provided a set of development tools including a compiler.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Unix/VADS could be hosted on a variety of Unix platforms such as DEC Ultrix and the Sun 3/60 Solaris targeted to Motorola 68020 in an Army CECOM evaluation.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] There were soon many Ada compilers available that passed the Ada Validation tests.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The Free Software Foundation GNU project developed the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) which provides a core capability to support multiple languages and targets.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The Ada version GNAT is one of the most widely used Ada compilers.
