[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] "When the field of compiling began in the late 50s, its focus was limited to the translation of high-level language programs into machine code ...
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The compiler field is increasingly intertwined with other disciplines including computer architecture, programming languages, formal methods, software engineering, and computer security." The "Compiler Research: The Next 50 Years" article noted the importance of object-oriented languages and Java.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Security and parallel computing were cited among the future research targets.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] A compiler implements a formal transformation from a high-level source program to a low-level target program.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Compiler design can define an end-to-end solution or tackle a defined subset that interfaces with other compiling tools e.g., preprocessors, assemblers, linkers.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Design requirements include rigorously defined interfaces both internally between compiler components and externally between supporting toolsets.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] In the early days, the approach taken to compiler design was directly affected by the complexity of the computer language to be processed, the experience of the person(s) designing it, and the resources available.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Resource limitations led to the need to pass through the source code more than once.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] A compiler for a relatively simple language written by one person might be a single, monolithic piece of software.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] However, as the source language grows in complexity the design may be split into a number of interdependent phases.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Separate phases provide design improvements that focus development on the functions in the compiling process.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Classifying compilers by number of passes has its background in the hardware resource limitations of computers.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Compiling involves performing much work and early computers did not have enough memory to contain one program that did all of this work.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] As a result, compilers were split up into smaller programs which each made a pass over the source (or some representation of it) performing some of the required analysis and translations.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The ability to compile in a single pass has classically been seen as a benefit because it simplifies the job of writing a compiler and one-pass compilers generally compile source code faster than multi-pass compilers.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Thus, partly driven by the resource limits of early systems, many early languages were specifically designed so that they could be compiled in one pass (e.g., Pascal).
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] In some cases, the design of a language feature may require a compiler to perform more than one pass over the source.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] For example, consider a declaration appearing on line 20 of the source which affects the translation of a statement appearing on line 10.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] In this case, the first pass needs to gather information about declarations appearing after statements that they affect, with the translation then performed during a subsequent pass.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The disadvantage of compiling in a single pass is that it is not possible to perform many of the sophisticated optimizations needed to generate high quality code.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] It can be difficult to count exactly how many passes an optimizing compiler makes.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] For instance, different phases of optimization may analyse one expression many times but only analyse another expression once.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Splitting a compiler up into small programs is a technique used by researchers interested in producing provably correct compilers.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Proving the correctness of a set of small programs often requires less effort than proving the correctness of a larger, single, equivalent program.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Regardless of the exact number of phases in the compiler design, the phases can be assigned to one of three stages.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The stages include a front end, a middle end, and a back end.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] This front/middle/back-end approach makes it possible to combine front ends for different languages with back ends for different CPUs while sharing the optimizations of the middle end.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Practical examples of this approach are the GNU Compiler Collection, Clang (LLVM-based C/C++ compiler), and the Amsterdam Compiler Kit, which have multiple front-ends, shared optimizations and multiple back-ends.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The front end analyzes the source code to build an internal representation of the program, called the intermediate representation (IR).
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] It also manages the symbol table, a data structure mapping each symbol in the source code to associated information such as location, type and scope.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] While the frontend can be a single monolithic function or program, as in a scannerless parser, it was traditionally implemented and analyzed as several phases, which may execute sequentially or concurrently.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] This method is favored due to its modularity and separation of concerns.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Most commonly, the frontend is broken into three phases: lexical analysis (also known as lexing or scanning), syntax analysis (also known as scanning or parsing), and semantic analysis.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Lexing and parsing comprise the syntactic analysis (word syntax and phrase syntax, respectively), and in simple cases, these modules (the lexer and parser) can be automatically generated from a grammar for the language, though in more complex cases these require manual modification.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The lexical grammar and phrase grammar are usually context-free grammars, which simplifies analysis significantly, with context-sensitivity handled at the semantic analysis phase.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The semantic analysis phase is generally more complex and written by hand, but can be partially or fully automated using attribute grammars.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] These phases themselves can be further broken down: lexing as scanning and evaluating, and parsing as building a concrete syntax tree (CST, parse tree) and then transforming it into an abstract syntax tree (AST, syntax tree).
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] In some cases additional phases are used, notably *line reconstruction* and *preprocessing,* but these are rare.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The middle end, also known as *optimizer,* performs optimizations on the intermediate representation in order to improve the performance and the quality of the produced machine code.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The middle end contains those optimizations that are independent of the CPU architecture being targeted.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Compiler analysis is the prerequisite for any compiler optimization, and they tightly work together.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] For example, dependence analysis is crucial for loop transformation.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The scope of compiler analysis and optimizations vary greatly; their scope may range from operating within a basic block, to whole procedures, or even the whole program.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] There is a trade-off between the granularity of the optimizations and the cost of compilation.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] For example, peephole optimizations are fast to perform during compilation but only affect a small local fragment of the code, and can be performed independently of the context in which the code fragment appears.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] In contrast, interprocedural optimization requires more compilation time and memory space, but enable optimizations that are only possible by considering the behavior of multiple functions simultaneously.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Interprocedural analysis and optimizations are common in modern commercial compilers from HP, IBM, SGI, Intel, Microsoft, and Sun Microsystems.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The free software GCC was criticized for a long time for lacking powerful interprocedural optimizations, but it is changing in this respect.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Another open source compiler with full analysis and optimization infrastructure is Open64, which is used by many organizations for research and commercial purposes.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Due to the extra time and space needed for compiler analysis and optimizations, some compilers skip them by default.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Users have to use compilation options to explicitly tell the compiler which optimizations should be enabled.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The back end is responsible for the CPU architecture specific optimizations and for code generation.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Compiler correctness is the branch of software engineering that deals with trying to show that a compiler behaves according to its language specification.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Techniques include developing the compiler using formal methods and using rigorous testing (often called compiler validation) on an existing compiler.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Higher-level programming languages usually appear with a type of translation in mind: either designed as compiled language or interpreted language.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] However, in practice there is rarely anything about a language that *requires* it to be exclusively compiled or exclusively interpreted, although it is possible to design languages that rely on re-interpretation at run time.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The categorization usually reflects the most popular or widespread implementations of a language.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] For instance, BASIC is sometimes called an interpreted language, and C a compiled one, despite the existence of BASIC compilers and C interpreters.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Interpretation does not replace compilation completely.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] It only hides it from the user and makes it gradual.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Even though an interpreter can itself be interpreted, a set of directly executed machine instructions is needed somewhere at the bottom of the execution stack (see machine language).
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Furthermore, for optimization compilers can contain interpreter functionality, and interpreters may include ahead of time compilation techniques.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] For example, where an expression can be executed during compilation and the results inserted into the output program, then it prevents it having to be recalculated each time the program runs, which can greatly speed up the final program.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Modern trends toward just-in-time compilation and bytecode interpretation at times blur the traditional categorizations of compilers and interpreters even further.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Meta-tracing is an automated compiler synthesis approach which takes this further and can be used to synthesize a compiler from a language interpreter.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Some language specifications spell out that implementations *must* include a compilation facility; for example, Common Lisp.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] However, there is nothing inherent in the definition of Common Lisp that stops it from being interpreted.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] To implement these features in a compiled language, programs must usually be shipped with a runtime library that includes a version of the compiler itself.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] One classification of compilers is by the platform on which their generated code executes.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] A *native* or *hosted* compiler is one whose output is intended to directly run on the same type of computer and operating system that the compiler itself runs on.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The output of a cross compiler is designed to run on a different platform.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Cross compilers are often used when developing software for embedded systems that are not intended to support a software development environment.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The output of a compiler that produces code for a virtual machine (VM) may or may not be executed on the same platform as the compiler that produced it.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] For this reason, such compilers are not usually classified as native or cross compilers.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The lower level language that is the target of a compiler may itself be a high-level programming language.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] C, viewed by some as a sort of portable assembly language, is frequently the target language of such compilers.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] For example, Cfront, the original compiler for C++, used C as its target language.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] The C code generated by such a compiler is usually not intended to be readable and maintained by humans, so indent style and creating pretty C intermediate code are ignored.
[src:reproducible-builds/compiler] Some of the features of C that make it a good target language include the `#line` directive, which can be generated by the compiler to support debugging of the original source, and the wide platform support available with C compilers.
[src:reproducible-builds/deterministic-algorithm] In computer science, a **deterministic algorithm** is an algorithm that, given a particular input, will always produce the same output, with the underlying machine always passing through the same sequence of states.
[src:reproducible-builds/deterministic-algorithm] Deterministic algorithms are by far the most studied and familiar kind of algorithm, as well as one of the most practical, since they can be run on real machines efficiently.
[src:reproducible-builds/deterministic-algorithm] Formally, a deterministic algorithm computes a mathematical function; a function has a unique value for any input in its domain, and the algorithm is a process that produces this particular value as output.
[src:reproducible-builds/deterministic-algorithm] Deterministic algorithms can be defined in terms of a state machine: a *state* describes what a machine is doing at a particular instant in time.
[src:reproducible-builds/deterministic-algorithm] State machines pass in a discrete manner from one state to another.
[src:reproducible-builds/deterministic-algorithm] Just after we enter the input, the machine is in its *initial state* or *start state*.
[src:reproducible-builds/deterministic-algorithm] If the machine is deterministic, this means that from this point onwards, its current state determines what its next state will be; its course through the set of states is predetermined.
[src:reproducible-builds/deterministic-algorithm] Note that a machine can be deterministic and still never stop or finish, and therefore fail to deliver a result.
[src:reproducible-builds/deterministic-algorithm] Examples of particular abstract machines which are deterministic include the deterministic Turing machine and deterministic finite automaton.
[src:reproducible-builds/deterministic-algorithm] Although real programs are rarely purely deterministic, it is easier for humans as well as other programs to reason about programs that are.
[src:reproducible-builds/deterministic-algorithm] For this reason, most programming languages and especially functional programming languages make an effort to prevent the above events from happening except under controlled conditions.
[src:reproducible-builds/deterministic-algorithm] The prevalence of multi-core processors has resulted in a surge of interest in determinism in parallel programming and challenges of non-determinism have been well documented.
[src:reproducible-builds/deterministic-algorithm] A number of tools to help deal with the challenges have been proposed to deal with deadlocks and race conditions.
[src:reproducible-builds/deterministic-algorithm] It is advantageous, in some cases, for a program to exhibit nondeterministic behavior.
[src:reproducible-builds/deterministic-algorithm] The behavior of a card shuffling program used in a game of blackjack, for example, should not be predictable by players — even if the source code of the program is visible.
[src:reproducible-builds/deterministic-algorithm] The use of a pseudorandom number generator is often not sufficient to ensure that players are unable to predict the outcome of a shuffle.
[src:reproducible-builds/deterministic-algorithm] These problems can be avoided, in part, through the use of a cryptographically secure pseudo-random number generator, but it is still necessary for an unpredictable random seed to be used to initialize the generator.
[src:reproducible-builds/deterministic-algorithm] For this purpose, a source of nondeterminism is required, such as that provided by a hardware random number generator.
[src:reproducible-builds/deterministic-algorithm] Note that a negative answer to the P=NP problem would not imply that programs with nondeterministic output are theoretically more powerful than those with deterministic output.
[src:reproducible-builds/deterministic-algorithm] The complexity class NP (complexity) can be defined without any reference to nondeterminism using the verifier-based definition.
[src:reproducible-builds/deterministic-algorithm] The mercury logic-functional programming language establishes different determinism categories for predicate modes as explained in the reference.
[src:reproducible-builds/deterministic-algorithm] In Java, the *null* reference value may represent an unsuccessful (out-of-domain) result.
[src:reproducible-builds/page] Getting reproducible builds for your software or distribution might be easier than you think.
[src:reproducible-builds/page] However, it might require small changes to your build system and a strategy on how to enable others to recreate an environment in which the builds can be reproduced.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] Reproducible builds can act as part of a chain of trust; the source code can be signed, and deterministic compilation can prove that the binary was compiled from trusted source code.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] Verified reproducible builds provide a strong countermeasure against attacks where binaries do not match their source code, e.g., because an attacker has inserted malicious code into a binary.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] This is a relevant attack; attackers sometimes attack binaries but not the source code, e.g., because they can only change the distributed binary or to evade detection since it is the source code that developers normally review and modify.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] In a survey of 17 experts, reproducible builds had a very high utility rating from 58.8% participants, but also a high-cost rating from 70.6%.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] Various efforts are being made to modify software development tools to reduce these costs.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] For the compilation process to be deterministic, the input to the compiler must be the same, regardless of the build environment used.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] This typically involves normalizing variables that may change, such as order of input files, timestamps, locales, and paths.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] Additionally, the compilers must not introduce non-determinism themselves.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] This sometimes happens when using hash tables with a random hash seed value.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] It can also happen when using the address of variables because that varies from address space layout randomization (ASLR).
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] Build systems, such as Bazel, GNU Guix, and Gitian, can be used to automate deterministic build processes.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] The GNU Project used reproducible builds in the early 1990s.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] Changelogs from 1992 indicate the ongoing effort.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] One of the older projects to promote reproducible builds is the Bitcoin project with Gitian, and later, GNU Guix.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] In 2013, the Tor (anonymity network) project started using Gitian for their reproducible builds.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] Starting in 2011, a reproducible Java build system was developed for the decentralized peer-to-peer FOSS project DirectDemocracyP2P.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] The concepts of the system's application to automated updates recommendation support was first presented in April 2013 at Decentralized Coordination.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] A treatise focusing on the implementation details of the reproducible Java compilation tool itself was published in 2015.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] In July 2013, the Debian project started implementing reproducible builds across its entire package archive.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] By July 2017, more than 90% of the packages in the repository were proven to build reproducibly.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] In November 2018, the Reproducible Builds project joined the Software Freedom Conservancy.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] F-Droid uses reproducible builds to provide a guarantee that distributed APKs use the claimed free source code.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] The Tails portable operating system uses reproducible builds and explains to others how to verify their distribution.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] NixOS claims 100% build reproducibility as of June 2021 for their minimal ISO releases.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] As of May 2020, Arch Linux is working on making all official packages reproducible.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] As of March 2025, Debian live images for Bookworm are reproducible.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] The FreeBSD operating system builds reproducibly and without root access since October 2025.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] According to the Reproducible Builds project, timestamps are "the biggest source of reproducibility issues.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] In some cases other changes must be made to make a build process reproducible.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] For example, some data structures do not guarantee a stable order in each execution.
[src:reproducible-builds/reproducible-builds] A typical solution is to modify the build process to specify a sorted output from those structures.
[src:reproducible-builds/software-distribution] GNU Autotools are widely used for which consist of source files written in C++ and the C programming language, but are not limited to these.
[src:reproducible-builds/software-distribution] Distribution of software to small mobile devices such as phones, PDAs and other hand-held terminals is a particular challenge due to their inconsistent connection to the Internet.
